<DOC><DOCNO> AP880329-0172 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2029EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Journalists-Noriega     03-29 0141</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Journalists-Noriega,0144</SECOND><HEAD>Journalists Cry Foul Over Treatment In Panama</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Overseas Press Club sent a letter to Gen.Manuel Antonio Noriega on Tuesday protesting what it described as``harsh treatment'' of foreign journalists in Panama City.   The organization of journalists said in a letter addressed tothe defense forces commander in Panama that the arrests of eightjournalists in Panama on Monday violated United Nations rules onhuman rights.   The journalists were arrested along with 20 opposition leaderswhen troops raided the Marriott Hotel, which serves as theheadquarters of Panama's opposition and the foreign press. Thejournalists were released Tuesday.   The letter, signed by Norman A. Schorr, chairman of the club'sFreedom of Press Committee, called on Noriega to protect the rightsof journalists to do their work ``free from harassment,intimidation and physical harm.''</TEXT></DOC>